20/ The CHRO decided that she needed to be the only voice in diversity and fired the Chief Diversity Officer and disbanded the department and let go employees who had been with the company for over 20 years.

19/ A friend at work got M to F reassignment surgery, gave her boss ample notice, and closed out assignments. Her boss texted her at the hospital harassing her about when she was coming back to work. That boss got a DE&I role, and knowing how she acted about that makes me sick.
18/ My manager in DE&I who was a black woman used words in front of me like "retarded," fully knowing that I was active in the disability resource group and had a learning disability.

17/ In the end I was let go from the company because I was "too expensive." I learned that after me they hired a black woman who was just out of school at 70% of my salary. Which is not even close to enough to live on in NYC.

16/ I called our HR hiring rep and tried to explain the situation and just got a "she fought for you." Mind you, I was expensing $50-70k a month for just two people at the time, and there was room in the budget but she brought in her lackey who made $100k+ to watch me work.

15/ She then started to yell at me, say I was lucky to no longer be an assistant. That was the best she could give me, and it was vulgar and disgusting to share salaries. Then she stormed out of the phone booth.

14/ I said to my manager "Isn't it bad optics to have someone in the CEO's office take a role with an almost 10% pay gap, especially after we made that big announcement? I have more experience at this role and have been doing it without that salary for a year."

13/ I was offered a new role at the time they announced this, (I worked on releasing the announcement and stayed late to put it out) and knew my male colleague made $75k a year at it and they were offering me $68k.

12/ On the "equity" part of DE&I, this is my worst story. The CEO put out a pledge to eliminate gender pay gap because they had to report it in the UK where we had an office and the difference was at about 20%. (cont. in next tweet).

11/ We had a Hackathon based on improving products for differently abled individuals and the ideas were excellent. I think the only one that got approved was something that made the newspaper more visible to readers with bigger font.
10/ As someone with ADHD I had a lot of insensitivity about it from colleagues, bosses, and ERGs. Because it's not visible and can't be shown off to make anyone look good it's seen as a problem.
9/ Unfortunately visibly disabled employees are often still used as a token of "we really are committed to DE&I" and placed front and center on the website to make companies look good.

8/ My ancestors are Spanish Inquisition Jews with a proud history of defying religious persecution. I went to a Latinx workshop and people thought I was just there to spy for the CEO. I'm really pale.

7/ I was placed into the DE&I department because I reported my former boss to HR for bullying me enough that I went back on SSRIs and back to therapy. She got me moved to a department she knew was a frustrating sinking ship.

6/ There was lots of drama, in-fighting, and throwing people under the bus within the ERGs because of lack of funding, frustration about releasing internal company comms, and the fact that at the end of the day it felt like it was all for show.

5/ We launched an initiative for women to rise up within the company, they all submitted long presentations and that entire process was still loaded with favoritism and tokenism and the DE&I dept. was not involved at all. It grossed me out.
4/ One of my more controversial statements- if you have an invisible disability even the ERGs for disabled employees will not take you seriously.

3/ ERGs aka Employee Resource Groups need to have adequate budgets to make change, put out initiatives and do programming. It's important for younger employees to see people in a position of leadership that look like them.
2/ The Chief Diversity Officer needs to report to the CEO. Period. None of this other person in between, it slows up everything and diminishes the importance of DE&I within the company.
1/ If the CEO and their staff don't take DE&I seriously nothing will ever get done. Budgets will take months to approve, speakers will not get booked, ERGs will get demoralized.

7/ These communities live on Discord and spill over to Twitter. Most are themed around a particular topic or cause, so it’s an excellent space to find your tribe and feel a sense of belonging. This is what your customers want, if you can't get there then you are NGMI.

6/ NFTs cont. Some NFT projects get you access to celebrities that also hold NFTs from the same collection @BoredApeYC, some are just gorgeous to look at and collect, some buy pieces in the Metaverse (that’s a whole other discussion). But mostly it’s about community.

5/ (My favorite) What are NFTS? 
You’ve heard about them, probably jumbled the letters. I’m not even going to explain what it stands for because it will not help you. NFTs are digitally stored and unique pieces of art, collectibles, etc. and are part of the Web3 ecosystem.

4/ Why do we buy this???
Cryptocurrency is a great way to invest, it’s not a bad idea to be an early adopter, you will love it once you see the percent gains. There are so many other reasons but for this purpose that’s what we’re focusing on.

9/ Metamask is probably one of the better basic wallets to have for buying NFTs. I know there are better options but this is a basic guide here and we don't need to shame people about their choices.

8/ Way to measure alpha: does the project have people listed as actually working there as a FT job? They're doing well. What's the volume of ETH that's been traded? Does a celeb own one and use it as a Twitter pfp? Then you should be doing well.
7/ It doesn't matter if you missed the mint on a particular project that's caught your eye, go and buy it on secondary if you like what the community is doing.
6/ Don't fall for any DMs on Discord. Stay the fuck back and don't give your seed phrase to anyone.
5/ Check Twitter, are you seeing a lot of pfp's of a particular project? Then it might be time to see what's up with it!
4/ Go to a project's @discord how active is it? Are people active? Do they have Twitter spaces? Collabs with other projects? Those will add value over time and build your community.

21/ If you're sending an invite to a CEO to join your cause, event, organization - get their assistant's name and send them an invite and gift as well. You are much more likely to get that participation.
@thatsavvygal Absolutely, do your research on the GP and assistant.

20/ Don't doubt yourself, most execs are flying by the seat of their pants. Just diving into major assignments happens a lot, you are often just as qualified to take something on as anyone else around you.

19/ When there are slow months (December) take the time to learn more about the company, study the players you'll be dealing with, read reports, talk to people who are around the office and also bored, go for coffees and network.
18/ Don't let your exec burn you out and take up your life. I made this mistake and it cost me a lot. Set up boundaries.

17/ Make sure to socialize away from your ivory tower and learn what everyone actually thinks. If there's any type of workshop to improve skills, sign up for it, get someone to cover for you for the day, it's good for your mental health.
16/ Take advantage of all of the face time that you will have with C Suite executives with 20+ years of career experience under their belts, listen, ask questions and take it in.
15/ There is an unseen hierarchy within the C-Suite, favorites of the CEO, favorite execs of the parent company, learn the relationships ASAP.
14/ Teach your exec accountability early, get them into the habit of just taking a picture of their receipts and texting them to you. It will make expense reporting less awful.
13/ Saving money and cutting corners while booking stuff for your boss won't get you any credit or more money in your bonus. It sucks.

12/ If you are working for a CEO you need to exude calm all the time. I am a frantic sprinter, and I learned from my mentors that I needed to slow down because everyone watches you and they will think the company is going to hell if the CEO's staff are running around frantically.
11/ For all of the power that you can be handed, don't be a jackass. Use it for good: try and help others get recognized and noticed by the C-suite when they do good work.
10/ Find a mentor immediately, preferably someone who has been at the company for years and has seen CEO turnover and knows everyone's business. They will be beyond helpful.
9/ If you mess up own up to it immediately and offer a solution. Don't throw anyone under the bus, it isn't worth it ever.
8/ No one has their shit together. You stop getting heroes once you see execs running around in pantyhose, drunk crying, puking, and refusing to promote people for bs reasons.
7/ Get to know every area of the company, every person in it, the org charts. All of this matters and will save you time later.
6/ Don't make yourself so indispensable that they don't want to promote you. It's a double edged sword.

5/ Optics are everything. If you are sending a gift on behalf of a CEO, make sure it lines up with where in the world they are. One time we got a letter with the ink still wet when the high profile Chairman who supposedly sent it was in jail. Saw right through that one.

4/ If you are trying to pitch a GP go to @PitchBook and find their assistant's name, if you call the GP's office phone, say "Hi, assistant's name, how are you? Can I speak to [their exec's name]. You will be remembered and more likely to get a meeting.
3/ An exec's EA most likely has their email inbox, and is ghostwriting their emails, don't say anything too revealing.
2/ When you send a gift to a C-Suite exec they almost never see it or take the gift, the EA gets it, and then if they don't want it, the Admin gets it.
1/ How you treat an executive's EA will determine your entire business relationship with that person. They control the calendar, if you're an asshole you will never get a meeting.
Things I learned as an Executive Assistant in the CEO's Office at a major media conglomerate a 🧵

11/You can't give up. I am sure it might take 65 more applications, but if you love this industry it is worth it.
10/The venture community will be helpful to get intros to get interviewed but they cannot get you the job. Entering that zoom call is a crap shoot every single time.

9/I am pretty sure that the same standards are still in place at a lot of VCs, if you're not from IB you're nothing, if you weren't a management consultant you're nothing, if you weren't a successful founder you're worthless. It's brutal.
8/ It is all about fit and completely subjective. You cannot take it personally, although it's often about personality.
7/ The entire system is chaotic.
6/Transparency as a whole was not great; very few listed salaries or benefits.
5/The rejection letters ran the gamut- a few were just automated (which is the worst) and there was one actually helpful rejection with feedback.
4/Turnaround time for the 10% of companies to get back to me was around 2-3 months.
3/The applicant pool with MBAs hovered around 20% for most of these positions. These were Associate level.
2/ Venture is just as competitive as ever. One role had 881 applicants.
1/ Of 65 roles I applied for my resume was downloaded for 26% of them, but I only heard anything from 10% of the companies.
What I learned from 65 rejections for roles in Venture Capital, a 🧵
